nd related CO2 hydrogenation chemistry on magnetite and reduced iron can generate reduced C1 organics that feed surface carbonyl chemistry; formaldehyde assignment is a network-connecting approximation grounded in hydrothermal reduction studies (McCollom and Seewald, 2007; He et al., 2010).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis of acetate from carbon dioxide and hydrogen\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent micropores; redox and pH gradients\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-bound one-carbon units are coupled and reduced on Fe-S minerals to give an acetyl equivalent that hydrolyzes to acetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetate formation from CO2/H2 on Fe-S mineral systems is central to the iron-sulfur world and acetyl-CoA analog hypotheses under hydrothermal conditions (Huber and Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal carboxylative synthesis of pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline to near-neutral hydrothermal flow; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced C1 and C2 intermediates are coupled and further oxidized/carboxylated on mineral surfaces to form the alpha-keto acid pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate has been reported among products and intermediates in metal-promoted protometabolic networks related to the reductive TCA and acetyl pathways, especially with Fe-based catalysts; this network step summarizes such hydrothermal alpha-keto acid generation (Muchowska et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface UV cyanosulfidic generation of hydrogen cyanide from formate-derived reduced carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; evaporitic concentration; anoxic atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical redox processing of reduced one-carbon nitrogenous species yields nitriles, represented here by HCN as a central feedstock.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN is a key surface feedstock in cyanosulfidic prebiotic chemistry and plausibly accumulates under UV-driven, reducing surface conditions; this conversion is a network-bridging condensation of literature-supported atmospheric and photochemical nitrile production themes (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2016).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Borate-stabilized dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals with photochemical assistance\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"intermittent drying; UV-exposed shallow pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde undergoes carbonyl addition and stabilization to C2 sugar aldehyde pools, with borate suppressing destructive side reactions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolaldehyde is a recognized product/feedstock in prebiotic sugar chemistry, and borate minerals can stabilize reactive carbohydrates under surface conditions (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol extension of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and clay surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles in evaporitic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol condensation adds a formaldehyde equivalent to glycolaldehyde, producing the triose glyceraldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction captures a canonical formose-type carbon chain extension, with borate helping preserve useful sugar products and clays concentrating reactants (Ricardo et al., 2004; Furukawa et al., 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker-type synthesis of alanine aminonitrile from acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrating pools; mildly acidic to neutral; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to produce the alpha-aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Strecker chemistry is a standard prebiotic route to alpha-aminonitriles and amino acids; aldehyde-derived aminonitriles are plausible in evaporitic pools and on mineral surfaces (Miller, 1957; Powner et al., 2009 for broader nitrile-rich prebiotic systems).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of alanine aminonitrile to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis during geothermal cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis proceeds through amide-like intermediates to the amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis is a classic completion step of Strecker amino acid synthesis and is widely accepted as a plausible prebiotic route to alanine (Miller, 1957; Bada and Lazcano, 2002).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent walls; reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate condenses with ammonia to an imine/iminium equivalent that is reduced on mineral surfaces to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids such as pyruvate is one of the most plausible direct routes to amino acids in hydrothermal settings, especially on transition-metal and Fe-S surfaces (Huber and Wachtershauser, 2003; Muchowska et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of pyruvate to lactate in prebiotic pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing microenvironments within mineral interfaces or protocells\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The alpha-keto group of pyruvate is reduced to the alpha-hydroxy acid lactate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Alpha-hydroxy acids are closely linked to alpha-keto acid chemistry in prebiotic systems, and lactate provides a useful branch point for further alanine generation through coupled redox or amination chemistry; this step is moderately speculative but chemically conservative (de Duve, 1995; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination-like conversion of lactate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal cycling; mineral interface-assisted redox-amination\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactate is oxidatively aminated through pyruvate-like intermediacy to give alanine in a net redox-neutral pool process.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Although direct lactate-to-alanine conversion is less established than pyruvate amination, alpha-hydroxy/alpha-keto acid interconversion coupled to nitrogen transfer is plausible in protometabolic settings and helps connect hydroxy acid and amino acid pools; this step is explicitly speculative but network-completing (Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"dry-heating or interfacial thermal pulses\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-keto acid decarboxylation releases CO2 and produces the corresponding aldehyde acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde is chemically well known and prebiotically plausible under heating, providing a bridge from protometabolic keto-acids to Strecker aldehyde chemistry (Copley et al., 2007; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN hydration to formamide under UV-active surface conditions\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; shallow pond concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydration and photochemical stabilization of HCN gives formamide as a persistent nitrile-derived intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is a prominent prebiotic solvent/reactant connected to HCN chemistry and UV/mineral-assisted synthesis on the early Earth surface (Saladino et al., 2012; Sutherland, 2016).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Condensation of glycolaldehyde with HCN and ammonia to 2-aminoacrolein\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals and montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanide-rich evaporitic pools; wet-dry concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbonyl activation and cyanide/nitrogen incorporation produce an unsaturated amino aldehyde/nitrile precursor represented here as 2-aminoacrolein.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminoacrylonitrile and aminoacrolein-type intermediates are plausible in nitrile-rich prebiotic networks and can serve as bridges between sugar and amino acid chemistry; this specific formulation is partly speculative but grounded in HCN-carbonyl condensation logic (Ferris and Orgel, 1966; Sutherland, 2016).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Conversion of 2-aminoacrolein to alanine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing prebiotic pool; geothermal cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrogenation and rearrangement of the unsaturated amino precursor yields the saturated alpha-aminonitrile alanine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is a speculative but chemically plausible reduction step that closes a route from carbonyl-cyanide condensates to the canonical Strecker intermediate alanine aminonitrile, allowing dense network connectivity between sugar and amino acid branches.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct hydrothermal reductive amination route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is reduced and assembled hydrothermally to pyruvate, which undergoes direct reductive amination on Fe-S minerals to L-alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate to lactate to alanine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate is transferred to prebiotic pools, reduced to lactate, and converted to alanine by redox-amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate decarboxylation followed by Strecker synthesis\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate decarboxylates to acetaldehyde, which then forms alanine aminonitrile in surface pools and hydrolyzes to L-alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate to HCN to Strecker route via pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formate feeds surface HCN production, while hydrothermal pyruvate supplies acetaldehyde; the two converge in Strecker alanine synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde-sugar branch feeding aminonitrile formation\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde enters borate-stabilized sugar chemistry, producing glycolaldehyde that participates in nitrile-rich amino precursor synthesis before converging on alanine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde side branch into alanine network\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde yields glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde in surface pools; glycolaldehyde also branches into amino precursor chemistry that returns to alanine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-formamide auxiliary route merging with Strecker alanine synthesis\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface HCN passes through formamide chemistry while the main aldehyde branch comes from pyruvate decarboxylation; both belong to the same nitrile-rich surface regime that yields alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetate-assisted hydrothermal pyruvate route to alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal acetate, together with formate, is converted to pyruvate and then directly aminated to alanine in vents.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetate-assisted hydrothermal pyruvate route via acetaldehyde Strecker branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal acetate contributes to pyruvate formation; pyruvate then decarboxylates to acetaldehyde for surface Strecker synthesis of alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Integrated cross-environment hub route\",\n      \"description\": \"This pathway explicitly traverses all three environments: hydrothermal carbon fixation generates formate, formaldehyde, acetate, and pyruvate; surface photochemistry generates HCN and sugar-derived amino precursors; biochemical hydrolysis completes alanine formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_011\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Alanine", "overall_strategy": "The network targets L-alanine through a densely connected prebiotic graph centered on four hubs: hydrogen cyanide, formaldehyde, pyruvate, and lactate. Hydrothermal chemistry fixes CO2 into formate, acetate, formaldehyde, and pyruvate on iron-sulfur and iron-oxide minerals. Surface environments convert hydrothermal feedstocks into sugars, nitriles, aminonitriles, and amino acids through cyanosulfidic photochemistry, Strecker-type chemistry, aldol chemistry, and wet-dry concentration on borate, sulfide, TiO2, phosphate, and clay minerals. Biochemical/prebiotic settings then interconvert pyruvate, lactate, acetaldehyde, and alanine by reductive amination, transamination, and peptide assembly. Ten valid pathways to L-alanine are embedded, with multiple convergent routes at pyruvate and acetaldehyde and cross-environment transfer from hydrothermal products to surface synthesis and then to biochemical assembly.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "ethanal, hydroxy-", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "ethanoic acid", "common_name": "acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H4N2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanenitrile", "common_name": "alanine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c1-3(5)2-4/h3H,5H2,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "L-alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)/t2-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanoic acid", "common_name": "lactic acid/lactate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2,4H,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C3H5NO", "iupac_name": "2-aminoprop-2-enal", "common_name": "2-aminoacrolein", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Greigite-catalyzed reduction of carbon dioxide to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions; anoxic; H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to surface-bound formyl/formate species followed by release into solution.", "reasoning": "Iron-sulfur minerals are widely invoked as catalysts for CO2 reduction under alkaline hydrothermal conditions, with greigite and FeS phases serving as analogs of biological Fe-S clusters; this is consistent with vent geochemistry and prebiotic carbon fixation proposals (Russell et al., 1994; Cody et al., 2000; Roldan et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Magnetite/iron reduction of carbon dioxide to formaldehyde via hydrothermal hydrogenation", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal; reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "CO2 undergoes sequential hydrogenation on iron oxide/metal surfaces to reduced C1 species including methanal.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type and related CO2 hydrogenation chemistry on magnetite and reduced iron can generate reduced C1 organics that feed surface carbonyl chemistry; formaldehyde assignment is a network-connecting approximation grounded in hydrothermal reduction studies (McCollom and Seewald, 2007; He et al., 2010)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of acetate from carbon dioxide and hydrogen", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent micropores; redox and pH gradients"}, "mechanism": "Surface-bound one-carbon units are coupled and reduced on Fe-S minerals to give an acetyl equivalent that hydrolyzes to acetate.", "reasoning": "Acetate formation from CO2/H2 on Fe-S mineral systems is central to the iron-sulfur world and acetyl-CoA analog hypotheses under hydrothermal conditions (Huber and Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal carboxylative synthesis of pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_009", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline to near-neutral hydrothermal flow; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Reduced C1 and C2 intermediates are coupled and further oxidized/carboxylated on mineral surfaces to form the alpha-keto acid pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate has been reported among products and intermediates in metal-promoted protometabolic networks related to the reductive TCA and acetyl pathways, especially with Fe-based catalysts; this network step summarizes such hydrothermal alpha-keto acid generation (Muchowska et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface UV cyanosulfidic generation of hydrogen cyanide from formate-derived reduced carbon", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; evaporitic concentration; anoxic atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical redox processing of reduced one-carbon nitrogenous species yields nitriles, represented here by HCN as a central feedstock.", "reasoning": "HCN is a key surface feedstock in cyanosulfidic prebiotic chemistry and plausibly accumulates under UV-driven, reducing surface conditions; this conversion is a network-bridging condensation of literature-supported atmospheric and photochemical nitrile production themes (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2016)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Borate-stabilized dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals with photochemical assistance", "aqueous": "true", "other": "intermittent drying; UV-exposed shallow pools"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde undergoes carbonyl addition and stabilization to C2 sugar aldehyde pools, with borate suppressing destructive side reactions.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde is a recognized product/feedstock in prebiotic sugar chemistry, and borate minerals can stabilize reactive carbohydrates under surface conditions (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Aldol extension of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and clay surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycles in evaporitic pools"}, "mechanism": "Aldol condensation adds a formaldehyde equivalent to glycolaldehyde, producing the triose glyceraldehyde.", "reasoning": "This reaction captures a canonical formose-type carbon chain extension, with borate helping preserve useful sugar products and clays concentrating reactants (Ricardo et al., 2004; Furukawa et al., 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Strecker-type synthesis of alanine aminonitrile from acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrating pools; mildly acidic to neutral; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to produce the alpha-aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "Strecker chemistry is a standard prebiotic route to alpha-aminonitriles and amino acids; aldehyde-derived aminonitriles are plausible in evaporitic pools and on mineral surfaces (Miller, 1957; Powner et al., 2009 for broader nitrile-rich prebiotic systems)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrolysis of alanine aminonitrile to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-360K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous hydrolysis during geothermal cycling"}, "mechanism": "Nitrile hydrolysis proceeds through amide-like intermediates to the amino acid.", "reasoning": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis is a classic completion step of Strecker amino acid synthesis and is widely accepted as a plausible prebiotic route to alanine (Miller, 1957; Bada and Lazcano, 2002)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite and greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent walls; reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate condenses with ammonia to an imine/iminium equivalent that is reduced on mineral surfaces to alanine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids such as pyruvate is one of the most plausible direct routes to amino acids in hydrothermal settings, especially on transition-metal and Fe-S surfaces (Huber and Wachtershauser, 2003; Muchowska et al., 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Reduction of pyruvate to lactate in prebiotic pools", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing microenvironments within mineral interfaces or protocells"}, "mechanism": "The alpha-keto group of pyruvate is reduced to the alpha-hydroxy acid lactate.", "reasoning": "Alpha-hydroxy acids are closely linked to alpha-keto acid chemistry in prebiotic systems, and lactate provides a useful branch point for further alanine generation through coupled redox or amination chemistry; this step is moderately speculative but chemically conservative (de Duve, 1995; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Transamination-like conversion of lactate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "geothermal cycling; mineral interface-assisted redox-amination"}, "mechanism": "Lactate is oxidatively aminated through pyruvate-like intermediacy to give alanine in a net redox-neutral pool process.", "reasoning": "Although direct lactate-to-alanine conversion is less established than pyruvate amination, alpha-hydroxy/alpha-keto acid interconversion coupled to nitrogen transfer is plausible in protometabolic settings and helps connect hydroxy acid and amino acid pools; this step is explicitly speculative but network-completing (Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_001"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "false", "other": "dry-heating or interfacial thermal pulses"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-keto acid decarboxylation releases CO2 and produces the corresponding aldehyde acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde is chemically well known and prebiotically plausible under heating, providing a bridge from protometabolic keto-acids to Strecker aldehyde chemistry (Copley et al., 2007; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "HCN hydration to formamide under UV-active surface conditions", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; shallow pond concentration"}, "mechanism": "Hydration and photochemical stabilization of HCN gives formamide as a persistent nitrile-derived intermediate.", "reasoning": "Formamide is a prominent prebiotic solvent/reactant connected to HCN chemistry and UV/mineral-assisted synthesis on the early Earth surface (Saladino et al., 2012; Sutherland, 2016)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Condensation of glycolaldehyde with HCN and ammonia to 2-aminoacrolein", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals and montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanide-rich evaporitic pools; wet-dry concentration"}, "mechanism": "Carbonyl activation and cyanide/nitrogen incorporation produce an unsaturated amino aldehyde/nitrile precursor represented here as 2-aminoacrolein.", "reasoning": "Aminoacrylonitrile and aminoacrolein-type intermediates are plausible in nitrile-rich prebiotic networks and can serve as bridges between sugar and amino acid chemistry; this specific formulation is partly speculative but grounded in HCN-carbonyl condensation logic (Ferris and Orgel, 1966; Sutherland, 2016)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Conversion of 2-aminoacrolein to alanine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing prebiotic pool; geothermal cycling"}, "mechanism": "Hydrogenation and rearrangement of the unsaturated amino precursor yields the saturated alpha-aminonitrile alanine aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "This reaction is a speculative but chemically plausible reduction step that closes a route from carbonyl-cyanide condensates to the canonical Strecker intermediate alanine aminonitrile, allowing dense network connectivity between sugar and amino acid branches."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Direct hydrothermal reductive amination route", "description": "CO2 is reduced and assembled hydrothermally to pyruvate, which undergoes direct reductive amination on Fe-S minerals to L-alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_009", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate to lactate to alanine route", "description": "Hydrothermal pyruvate is transferred to prebiotic pools, reduced to lactate, and converted to alanine by redox-amination.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Pyruvate decarboxylation followed by Strecker synthesis", "description": "Hydrothermal pyruvate decarboxylates to acetaldehyde, which then forms alanine aminonitrile in surface pools and hydrolyzes to L-alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_013", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Formate to HCN to Strecker route via pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde", "description": "Hydrothermal formate feeds surface HCN production, while hydrothermal pyruvate supplies acetaldehyde; the two converge in Strecker alanine synthesis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_013", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_004", "mol_014", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Formaldehyde-sugar branch feeding aminonitrile formation", "description": "Hydrothermal formaldehyde enters borate-stabilized sugar chemistry, producing glycolaldehyde that participates in nitrile-rich amino precursor synthesis before converging on alanine aminonitrile.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_016", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde side branch into alanine network", "description": "Hydr