ermal intermediates", "Provide explicit mineral and pH gradient details for the alanine-forming amination step", "Avoid overclaiming direct production of L-alanine rather than alanine generally"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.86, "rxn_003": 0.8, "rxn_004": 0.62, "rxn_013": 0.88, "rxn_005": 0.22, "rxn_008": 0.9, "rxn_009": 0.88}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.74, "pathway_coherence": 0.84, "environmental_progression": 0.88, "target_achievement": 0.91, "overall_confidence": 0.79, "feedback": "A strong acetaldehyde-Strecker route embedded in a reasonable hydrothermal-to-surface progression. The route would likely be approvable if the cyanide generation were improved. As written, the weak rxn_005 drags confidence below approval threshold.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005"], "suggestions": ["Swap rxn_005 for a defensible HCN delivery mechanism", "Add hydrolysis conditions for aminonitrile conversion if environmental continuity matters", "Keep this as a key route after revising cyanide sourcing"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.86, "rxn_003": 0.8, "rxn_004": 0.62, "rxn_013": 0.88, "rxn_005": 0.22, "rxn_008": 0.9, "rxn_009": 0.88, "rxn_006": 0.71, "rxn_007": 0.83}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.71, "pathway_coherence": 0.82, "environmental_progression": 0.92, "target_achievement": 0.9, "overall_confidence": 0.78, "feedback": "This integrated pathway best demonstrates the intended network architecture and environmental interconnection. Hydrothermal fixed carbon feeds both pyruvate chemistry and surface carbonyl chemistry, then merges into Strecker alanine synthesis. Still, some side-branch steps are ornamental rather than causally necessary, and the HCN source remains the principal chemical weakness.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005"], "suggestions": ["Preserve this as the showcase topology pathway but revise the cyanide module", "Clarify which side-branch reactions are essential versus auxiliary", "Strengthen literature support for hydrothermal pyruvate generation"]}], "best_pathway_id": "P1", "overall_confidence": 0.74, "network_feedback": "The network is topologically strong: it has sufficient size, good connectivity, multiple hubs, several convergence points, and clear Hydrothermal -> Surface -> Biochemical flow. Mineralized hydrothermal and surface chemistry is conceptually appropriate, and the target molecule is reached by several distinct routes. However, chemical quality is uneven. The strongest components are CO2 to formate/acetate, pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde, Strecker synthesis of alanine aminonitrile, and aminonitrile hydrolysis to alanine. Major weaknesses are the poorly supported generation of HCN from formate plus ammonia under surface UV conditions, the compressed and weakly justified hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis step, the implausible direct lactate-to-alanine conversion, and the speculative 2-aminoacrolein branch. The designation of the target as specifically L-alanine is not justified by any chiral induction step; the network supports alanine formation more generally. No literature citations are provided in the reaction reasoning, which lowers confidence under the stated evaluation rubric. Overall, this is a good network architecture with several plausible subroutes, but not yet a fully convincing complete synthesis network for prebiotic L-alanine.", "approved": true, "hub_quality": 0.87, "convergence_quality": 0.84}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 74239.59589004517, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T00:29:01.052442", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Alanine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.74\n- Feedback: The network is topologically strong: it has sufficient size, good connectivity, multiple hubs, several convergence points, and clear Hydrothermal -> Surface -> Biochemical flow. Mineralized hydrothermal and surface chemistry is conceptually appropriate, and the target molecule is reached by several distinct routes. However, chemical quality is uneven. The strongest components are CO2 to formate/acetate, pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde, Strecker synthesis of alanine aminonitrile, and aminonitrile hydrolysis to alanine. Major weaknesses are the poorly supported generation of HCN from formate plus ammonia under surface UV conditions, the compressed and weakly justified hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis step, the implausible direct lactate-to-alanine conversion, and the speculative 2-aminoacrolein branch. The designation of the target as specifically L-alanine is not justified by any chiral induction step; the network supports alanine formation more generally. No literature citations are provided in the reaction reasoning, which lowers confidence under the stated evaluation rubric. Overall, this is a good network architecture with several plausible subroutes, but not yet a fully convincing complete synthesis network for prebiotic L-alanine.\n- Issues: ['The pyruvate-to-lactate reduction is chemically plausible, but the final lactate-to-alanine conversion is the major failure point. A direct transamination-like conversion from lactate and ammonia to alanine is not chemically convincing because lactate is an alpha-hydroxy acid, not an alpha-keto acid. This route would require prior oxidation to pyruvate or another activation step.', 'This is a strong integrated route except for the HCN-generation step. Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde is plausible, and Strecker synthesis plus aminonitrile hydrolysis is well grounded. However, rxn_005 is weakly specified and not a standard or well-supported transformation from formate plus ammonia to HCN under surface UV conditions.', 'Good cross-environment logic: hydrothermal fixed carbon feeds surface cyanide/Strecker chemistry. The weak point remains rxn_005, which undermines an otherwise plausible acetaldehyde-to-alanine aminonitrile route. The rest of the sequence is chemically recognizable and reaches alanine cleanly.', 'This branch is the weakest in the network. Hydrothermal direct reduction of CO2 to formaldehyde is possible only under limited conditions and often gives mixtures. More importantly, the glycolaldehyde/HCN/ammonia condensation to 2-aminoacrolein and its hydrogenation to alanine aminonitrile are highly speculative and not presented as standard prebiotic chemistry.', 'The sugar chemistry segment is acceptable: formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde and then to glyceraldehyde under borate-influenced surface conditions is plausible. But the claimed feed into alanine synthesis through 2-aminoacrolein is poorly supported and appears forced. Glyceraldehyde itself is not actually used to reach the target in a chemically clear way.', 'The formamide auxiliary branch is plausible in isolation, but it does not materially improve the route to alanine because formamide is not actually used downstream in the listed reactions. This makes the pathway feel inflated. The same weak HCN-generation step remains the major liability.', 'A strong acetaldehyde-Strecker route embedded in a reasonable hydrothermal-to-surface progression. The route would likely be approvable if the cyanide generation were improved. As written, the weak rxn_005 drags confidence below approval threshold.', 'This integrated pathway best demonstrates the intended network architecture and environmental interconnection. Hydrothermal fixed carbon feeds both pyruvate chemistry and surface carbonyl chemistry, then merges into Strecker alanine synthesis. Still, some side-branch steps are ornamental rather than causally necessary, and the HCN source remains the principal chemical weakness.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Alanine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network targets alanine formation through a dense prebiotic graph centered on four hub intermediates: hydrogen cyanide, pyruvate, acetaldehyde, and alanine aminonitrile. Hydrothermal vent chemistry fixes carbon from CO2 into formate, acetate, pyruvate, and acetaldehyde on iron-sulfur and iron-oxide minerals. Surface environments generate and concentrate cyanide-derived intermediates, enable Strecker chemistry, and support hydrolysis under wet-dry cycling. Biochemical/prebiotic settings connect hydrothermal keto-acid chemistry with surface aminonitrile chemistry through reductive amination, transamination, and aminonitrile hydrolysis. Because no credible prebiotic enantioselective induction is established here, the network reaches alanine generically and treats L-alanine as the biological target obtainable after later chiral selection or amplification in protocell-associated environments.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid/formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvic acid/pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H5NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c1-3(5)2-4/h3H,1,5H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCONH2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-diaminomaleonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DAMN\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Greigite-catalyzed reduction of carbon dioxide to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to surface-bound formyl equivalents that are released as formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals is a central vent-chemistry step and is supported by iron-sulfur world and hydrothermal CO2 reduction studies; greigite and related FeS phases are commonly invoked as analogs of biological Fe-S active sites (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Further hydrothermal carbon fixation from formate to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing alkaline vent setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential reduction and C-C bond formation generate acetyl-level products released as acetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetate formation from CO2-derived one-carbon intermediates under hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis is widely discussed as an analog of acetyl-CoA pathway chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019; Varma et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from fixed carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent fluids with pH gradient\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-promoted reductive carbon fixation and carboxylation assemble a three-carbon alpha-keto acid from CO2-derived C1/C2 building blocks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate and related carboxylic acids have been reported from hydrothermal-style nonenzymatic carbon-fixation systems using transition-metal catalysts, though exact route details remain partly unresolved; this step is plausible but still a bottleneck in prebiotic network construction (Muchowska et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"thermal decarboxylation during geothermal cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-keto acid decarboxylation produces acetaldehyde and CO2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde is a chemically straightforward transformation of alpha-keto acids and provides a robust link from hydrothermal carbon fixation to Strecker chemistry. This step is consistent with known thermal and mineral-assisted alpha-keto acid decarboxylation behavior in prebiotic models.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrothermal generation of formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic subseafloor or vent chimney interfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Partial reduction of CO2 under FTT-like conditions yields simple oxygenated organics including formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal FTT-type chemistry on iron minerals can generate mixtures of reduced carbon compounds including aldehydes. Formaldehyde formation is mixture-prone and less selective than formate production, but it is a plausible feeder into surface sugar chemistry (Cody et al., 2000; McCollom & Seewald, 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aldol coupling of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate/TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pools with UV exposure and concentration by drying\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of formaldehyde equivalents produces the two-carbon sugar aldehyde, with borate stabilizing polyol products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolaldehyde is a canonical product/intermediate in formose-like networks, and borate minerals are known to stabilize sugar products under prebiotic surface conditions; UV-active mineral settings can assist carbonyl chemistry and concentration (Benner et al., 2012; Ricardo et al., 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aldol extension of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling in shallow pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol addition of a one-carbon carbonyl donor to glycolaldehyde yields the triose glyceraldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formation of glyceraldehyde from lower aldehydes is part of classic formose-type chemistry, and borate improves persistence of sugars otherwise prone to decomposition (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical formation and concentration of hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated subaerial geothermal field; dehydration/re-equilibration of formamide-rich residues\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven degradation/rearrangement of formamide-rich cyanide chemistry generates HCN as part of a dynamic nitrile pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction avoids the previously weak formate-plus-ammonia cyanide step. Formamide is a recognized prebiotic nitrogen-carbon feedstock under UV-active conditions, and HCN/formamide interconversion belongs to the broader nitrile chemistry landscape. Exact yields vary and environmental sourcing of HCN remains an open systems-level issue; here it is used as a plausible surface reservoir rather than a sole genesis route (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to diaminomaleonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporative concentration with UV exposure\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN tetramerization produces DAMN through nitrile addition and imine tautomerization steps.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"DAMN is a well-established HCN oligomerization product and an indicator of concentrated cyanide chemistry on the early Earth (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; S\u00e1nchez et al., 1967).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis and photolysis cycling of DAMN to regenerate HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV cycling and partial hydrolysis in shallow ponds\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reversible cyanide oligomer chemistry and partial breakdown of DAMN feed back into the free HCN pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN oligomer chemistry is reversible at the network level and contributes to buffered nitrile inventories under cycling conditions; this step is included to create realistic cyanide-network connectivity rather than a one-way sink (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of alanine aminonitrile from acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous evaporitic pools with concentration during drying\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to give the alpha-aminonitrile precursor of alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the strongest canonical prebiotic route to alanine precursor formation: Strecker synthesis from acetaldehyde, ammonia, and HCN is well established and chemically direct (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1957; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic hydrothermal setting with mineral-bound reducing power\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes imine formation with ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is one of the most plausible direct prebiotic amino acid-forming processes in hydrothermal settings, especially for alanine from pyruvate (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2017). This route yields alanine without invoking weak hydroxy-acid amination chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of alanine aminonitrile to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles or mildly heated aqueous pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydration and hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile into the corresponding amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of Strecker aminonitriles to amino acids is standard chemistry and is a key completion step for many prebiotic amino acid routes (Miller, 1957; Danger et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface oxidation-rearrangement of glyceraldehyde to pyruvate-like keto acid pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated shallow pools with phosphate-assisted carbonyl transformations\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical oxidation and carbonyl rearrangement convert triose aldehydes into alpha-keto acid products including pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct high-yield glyceraldehyde-to-pyruvate conversion is less established than the core Strecker route, so this step is moderately speculative but chemically motivated by known oxidative fragmentation/rearrangement of sugars toward carboxylates and alpha-keto acids in prebiotic networks. It is included to create a second environmental route into the pyruvate hub.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical transamination from pyruvate using alanine as amino donor\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mineral interfaces or concentrated pools; network-level amino group exchange\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Once alanine appears, reversible amino transfer can amplify alanine within a keto-acid pool by autocatalytic-like network recycling.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nonenzymatic transamination among keto acids and amino acids is prebiotically relevant in metal-rich systems. This reaction is represented as a network-propagation step rather than net de novo synthesis, showing how initial alanine production could reinforce further alanine accumulation (Mayer et al., 2014; Muchowska et al., 2017).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct hydrothermal reductive amination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Carbon is fixed hydrothermally to pyruvate, which is directly converted to alanine on iron-sulfur minerals.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate to acetaldehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate is decarboxylated to acetaldehyde, then surface Strecker chemistry forms alanine aminonitrile followed by hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetate-assisted carbon fixation branch to alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Formate is extended to acetate and then into pyruvate-equivalent carbon fixation chemistry before reductive amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde-sugar-pyruvate-hydrothermal amination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde feeds surface sugar chemistry to glyceraldehyde, which is transformed into pyruvate and then to alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde-sugar-pyruvate-Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface sugar chemistry furnishes pyruvate, which is decarboxylated to acetaldehyde and enters Strecker synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-buffered Strecker route via DAMN recycling\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface HCN is buffered through oligomerization to DAMN and release back to cyanide, then used in Strecker alanine precursor synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal to surface cross-environment alanine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal fixed carbon gives acetaldehyde while surface nitrile chemistry supplies HCN; they converge in Strecker synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-entry pyruvate convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate can be reached either hydrothermally or from surface sugar oxidation; once formed, it enters direct alanine synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Aminonitrile-first biochemical completion route\",\n      \"description\": \"The chemically strongest carbon-nitrogen coupling occurs at the aminonitrile stage, which is then hydrolyzed in prebiotic pools to alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Alanine amplification through keto-acid transamination network\",\n      \"description\": \"Once initial alanine is formed by either direct hydrothermal amination or aminonitrile hydrolysis, reversible transamination within a pyruvate-rich pool can reinforce alanine accumulation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_010\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Alanine", "overall_strategy": "This network targets alanine formation through a dense prebiotic graph centered on four hub intermediates: hydrogen cyanide, pyruvate, acetaldehyde, and alanine aminonitrile. Hydrothermal vent chemistry fixes carbon from CO2 into formate, acetate, pyruvate, and acetaldehyde on iron-sulfur and iron-oxide minerals. Surface environments generate and concentrate cyanide-derived intermediates, enable Strecker chemistry, and support hydrolysis under wet-dry cycling. Biochemical/prebiotic settings connect hydrothermal keto-acid chemistry with surface aminonitrile chemistry through reductive amination, transamination, and aminonitrile hydrolysis. Because no credible prebiotic enantioselective induction is established here, the network reaches alanine generically and treats L-alanine as the biological target obtainable after later chiral selection or amplification in protocell-associated environments.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "acetic acid", "common_name": "acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid/pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H5NO", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanenitrile", "common_name": "alanine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c1-3(5)2-4/h3H,1,5H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "HCONH2", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H8N4", "iupac_name": "2,3-diaminomaleonitrile", "common_name": "DAMN", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Greigite-catalyzed reduction of carbon dioxide to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to surface-bound formyl equivalents that are released as formate.", "reasoning": "Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals is a central vent-chemistry step and is supported by iron-sulfur world and hydrothermal CO2 reduction studies; greigite and related FeS phases are commonly invoked as analogs of biological Fe-S active sites (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Further hydrothermal carbon fixation from formate to acetate", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-420K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing alkaline vent setting"}, "mechanism": "Sequential reduction and C-C bond formation generate acetyl-level products released as acetate.", "reasoning": "Acetate formation from CO2-derived one-carbon intermediates under hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis is widely discussed as an analog of acetyl-CoA pathway chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019; Varma et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from fixed carbon", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent fluids with pH gradient"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-promoted reductive carbon fixation and carboxylation assemble a three-carbon alpha-keto acid from CO2-derived C1/C2 building blocks.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate and related carboxylic acids have been reported from hydrothermal-style nonenzymatic carbon-fixation systems using transition-metal catalysts, though exact route details remain partly unresolved; this step is plausible but still a bottleneck in prebiotic network construction (Muchowska et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_001"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "thermal decarboxylation during geothermal cycling"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-keto acid decarboxylation produces acetaldehyde and CO2.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde is a chemically straightforward transformation of alpha-keto acids and provides a robust link from hydrothermal carbon fixation to Strecker chemistry. This step is consistent with known thermal and mineral-assisted alpha-keto acid decarboxylation behavior in prebiotic models."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrothermal generation of formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic subseafloor or vent chimney interfaces"}, "mechanism": "Partial reduction of CO2 under FTT-like conditions yields simple oxygenated organics including formaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal FTT-type chemistry on iron minerals can generate mixtures of reduced carbon compounds including aldehydes. Formaldehyde formation is mixture-prone and less selective than formate production, but it is a plausible feeder into surface sugar chemistry (Cody et al., 2000; McCollom & Seewald, 2007)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface aldol coupling of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate/TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pools with UV exposure and concentration by drying"}, "mechanism": "Condensation of formaldehyde equivalents produces the two-carbon sugar aldehyde, with borate stabilizing polyol products.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde is a canonical product/intermediate in formose-like networks, and borate minerals are known to stabilize sugar products under prebiotic surface conditions; UV-active mineral settings can assist carbonyl chemistry and concentration (Benner et al., 2012; Ricardo et al., 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface aldol extension of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycling in shallow pools"}, "mechanism": "Aldol addition of a one-carbon carbonyl donor to glycolaldehyde yields the triose glyceraldehyde.", "reasoning": "Formation of glyceraldehyde from lower aldehydes is part of classic formose-type chemistry, and borate improves persistence of sugars otherwise prone to decomposition (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface photochemical formation and concentration of hydrogen cyanide", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated subaerial geothermal field; dehydration/re-equilibration of formamide-rich residues"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven degradation/rearrangement of formamide-rich cyanide chemistry generates HCN as part of a dynamic nitrile pool.", "reasoning": "This reaction avoids the previously weak formate-plus-ammonia cyanide step. Formamide is a recognized prebiotic nitrogen-carbon feedstock under UV-active conditions, and HCN/formamide interconversion belongs to the broader nitrile chemistry landscape. Exact yields vary and environmental sourcing of HCN remains an open systems-level issue; here it is used as a plausible surface reservoir rather than a sole genesis route (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "HCN oligomerization to diaminomaleonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporative concentration with UV exposure"}, "mechanism": "HCN tetramerization produces DAMN through nitrile addition and imine tautomerization steps.", "reasoning": "DAMN is a well-established HCN oligomerization product and an indicator of concentrated cyanide chemistry on the early Earth (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; S\u00e1nchez et al., 1967)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrolysis and photolysis cycling of DAMN to regenerate HCN", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV cycling and partial hydrolysis in shallow ponds"}, "mechanism": "Reversible cyanide oligomer chemistry and partial breakdown of DAMN feed back into the free HCN pool.", "reasoning": "HCN oligomer chemistry is reversible at the network level and contributes to buffered nitrile inventories under cycling conditions; this step is included to create realistic cyanide-network connectivity rather than a one-way sink (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Strecker synthesis of alanine aminonitrile from acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous evaporitic pools with concentration during drying"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to give the alpha-aminonitrile precursor of alanine.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest canonical prebiotic route to alanine precursor formation: Strecker synthesis from acetaldehyde, ammonia, and HCN is well established and chemically direct (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1957; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic hydrothermal setting with mineral-bound reducing power"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes imine formation with ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction to alanine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is one of the most plausible direct prebiotic amino acid-forming processes in hydrothermal settings, especially for alanine from pyruvate (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2017). This route yields alanine without invoking weak hydroxy-acid amination chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydrolysis of alanine aminonitrile to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycles or mildly heated aqueous pools"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise nitrile hydration and hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile into the corresponding amino acid.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of Strecker aminonitriles to amino acids is standard chemistry and is a key completion step for many prebiotic amino acid routes (Miller, 1957; Danger et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Surface oxidation-rearrangement of glyceraldehyde to pyruvate-like keto acid pool", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated shallow pools with phosphate-assisted carbonyl transformations"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical oxidation and carbonyl rearrangement convert triose aldehydes into alpha-keto acid products including pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Direct high-yield glyceraldehyde-to-pyruvate conversion is less established than the core Strecker route, so this step is moderately speculative but chemically motivated by known oxidative fragmentation/rearrangement of sugars toward carboxylates and alpha-keto acids in prebiotic networks. It is included to create a second environmental route into the pyruvate hub."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Biochemical transamination from pyruvate using alanine as amino donor", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "mineral interfaces or concentrated pools; network-level amino group exchange"}, "mechanism": "Once alanine appears, reversible amino transfer can amplify alanine within a keto-acid pool by autocatalytic-like network recycling.", "reasoning": "Nonenzymatic transamination among keto acids and amino acids is prebiotically relevant in metal-rich systems. This reaction is represented as a network-propagation step rather than net de novo synthesis, showing how initial alanine production could reinforce further alanine accumulation (Mayer et al., 2014; Muchowska et al., 2017)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Direct hydrothermal reductive amination route", "description": "Carbon is fixed hydrothermally to pyruvate, which is directly converted to alanine on iron-sulfur minerals.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_007"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate to acetaldehyde Strecker route", "description": "Hydrothermal pyruvate is decarboxylated to acetaldehyde, then surface Strecker chemistry forms alanine aminonitrile fo