pecific energetic context and competing products. The rest of the route is plausible, especially Strecker chemistry and aminonitrile hydrolysis.', 'The branch is reasonable as a hydrothermal carbon-fixation variant, but acetate is not clearly required if pyruvate is already produced directly in rxn_003. This makes the pathway somewhat redundant rather than mechanistically convergent. Still, the hydrothermal chemistry is mostly plausible.', 'This route is the weakest major pathway. Formaldehyde generation under hydrothermal conditions is possible but not robust as presented, rxn_006 is chemically problematic because a single formaldehyde molecule cannot simply become glycolaldehyde without an additional carbon source, and rxn_014 is especially speculative because glyceraldehyde-to-pyruvate is not a standard direct prebiotic transformation.', 'This route suffers from compounding weaknesses: problematic formaldehyde-to-glycolaldehyde stoichiometry, a speculative glyceraldehyde-to-pyruvate step, and an underjustified formamide-to-HCN step. Although the later Strecker and hydrolysis stages are good, the upstream chemistry is too uncertain.', 'HCN oligomerization to DAMN is strong, and DAMN/HCN photochemical cycling is directionally plausible. But this pathway depends heavily on rxn_008, which is weakly framed. If HCN availability were better justified, this route would become much stronger.', 'This pathway best showcases hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical flow and has good narrative coherence. It is close to approval, but still limited by reliance on the weak formamide-to-HCN step and the moderately speculative direct pyruvate synthesis step.', 'The idea of dual-entry convergence on pyruvate is good topologically, but one branch is much weaker than the other. The sugar-derived pyruvate route is too speculative and chemically underdefined, so convergence at pyruvate is not convincingly demonstrated.', 'The transamination/amplification concept is poorly implemented. rxn_015 is not chemically balanced as written because alanine cannot act as amino donor to pyruvate and regenerate net alanine without a distinct amino donor/acceptor pair. This undermines the pathway.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Alanine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network targets alanine through chemically stronger, literature-grounded routes centered on four hubs: pyruvate, acetaldehyde, hydrogen cyanide, and alanine aminonitrile. Hydrothermal chemistry fixes carbon from CO2 to formate, acetate, pyruvate, and acetaldehyde on iron-sulfur and oxide minerals. Surface chemistry supplies cyanide, aminonitrile formation, and hydrolysis under mineral-assisted wet-dry and UV regimes. Biochemical/prebiotic stages complete hydrolysis, transamination, and chiral enrichment/selection. Because abiotic syntheses generally yield racemic alanine, the network treats alanine formation as prebiotically plausible first, then routes to L-enrichment through mineral- and peptide-mediated selection rather than assuming primary enantioselective synthesis. Ten distinct connected pathways are defined to the target, with convergences at HCN, acetaldehyde, pyruvate, and alanine aminonitrile.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"