\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHNO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c1-3(4)2-5/h3H,4H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)/t2-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Greigite-catalyzed reduction of CO2 to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-mediated two-electron reduction of CO2 by H2 on iron-sulfur minerals yields adsorbed formate/formic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of CO2 to formate on FeS-family minerals is a core hydrothermal carbon-fixation step and is consistent with vent geochemistry and iron-sulfur world models (Martin et al., 2008; Barge et al., 2019; Roldan et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal homologation of formate to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"vent wall microcompartments, reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formyl and carbonyl fragments generated on Fe-S surfaces couple and are further reduced to C2 carboxylate products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis supports acetyl/thioester analog formation and acetate generation from CO2-, CO-, and H2-derived fragments (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Mineral-mediated synthesis of pyruvate from fixed C1/C2 carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic hydrothermal flow, redox and pH gradients\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential carbon fixation and carboxylation on mineral surfaces extend C1/C2 units to the alpha-keto acid pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is among the more plausible alpha-keto acid products in hydrothermal protometabolic networks, though exact mechanistic sequences remain partially unresolved; inclusion here connects experimentally supported C1/C2 fixation chemistry to protometabolic C3 products (Muchowska et al., 2019; Varma et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"thermal pulses in geothermal settings\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-keto acid decarboxylation releases CO2 and forms the corresponding aldehyde, acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde is chemically well established and provides a strong bridge from protometabolic keto-acids to Strecker-ready aldehydes under prebiotic heating regimes (Miller, 1957; Weber, 1981).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type formation of acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal, anoxic reducing fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO hydrogenation on metal/oxide surfaces generates mixed oxygenates including aldehydes such as acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrothermal synthesis on magnetite and reduced iron is a plausible source of simple aldehydes and alcohols, providing an independent route to acetaldehyde (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of CO2-derived carbon to formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing hydrothermal fluids; mixed products expected\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Partial reduction of CO2 on reduced mineral surfaces yields low-molecular-weight oxygenates including formaldehyde in product mixtures.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formaldehyde production under hydrothermal reducing conditions is less selective than formate formation but remains plausible as part of mixed carbonyl inventories later concentrated at the surface; this step is included cautiously as a minor feeder route (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Cleaves, 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Photochemical generation of HCN from formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, evaporitic or geothermal pool margins, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-assisted dehydration/photolysis of formamide on mineral surfaces furnishes nitrile-bearing products including HCN.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide photochemistry is a widely discussed prebiotic source of cyanide-derived chemistry and nucleobase precursors under UV-irradiated mineral conditions (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface generation of HCN from formaldehyde and ammonia under UV-active conditions\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, drying-concentration cycles, anoxic atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical and redox-active surface chemistry converts reduced C1 carbonyl/nitrogen mixtures into nitrile products including HCN.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct high-yield formaldehyde-to-HCN conversion is not a single canonical step, but UV-driven atmospheric and surface networks can generate HCN from reduced C/N feedstocks; here it is included as a connected feeder route to the cyanide pool rather than as an exclusive source (Patel et al., 2015; Rimmer & Rugheimer, 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formamide formation from formate and ammonia during drying\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles, dehydration in geothermal fields\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Drying-induced condensation of formate-derived formic acid equivalents with ammonia gives formamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is plausibly concentrated and generated in drying surface environments from simple C1 precursors and ammonia, and serves as a key cyanide-related intermediate (Saladino et al., 2012; Pasek & Lauretta, 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of alanine aminonitrile from acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pools or tidal flats, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to produce 2-aminopropanenitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker route from acetaldehyde to alanine aminonitrile is among the strongest and most classic prebiotic pathways to alanine precursors (Miller, 1953; Miller, 1957; Powner et al., 2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of alanine aminonitrile to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal pools, repeated hydration-heating cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydration and subsequent hydrolysis convert the aminonitrile to the amino acid alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis is the standard completion step of Strecker amino-acid synthesis and is strongly grounded in prebiotic amino acid chemistry (Miller, 1957; Bada, 1991).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent, reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate condenses with ammonia to an imine/iminium equivalent that is reduced on mineral surfaces to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is a chemically strong route to amino acids under reducing prebiotic conditions, especially on metal and sulfide surfaces; pyruvate-to-alanine is one of the most plausible examples (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2006; Muchowska et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Prebiotic transamination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mineral interface or concentrated pool; network amplification step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alanine or related amine donors can promote amino-group transfer equilibria centered on pyruvate, reinforcing alanine accumulation within a protometabolic network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is an explicitly network-level amplification step rather than a net synthetic origin step; nonenzymatic transamination around alpha-keto acids is plausible, but exact alanine-autocoupled stoichiometry is simplified here to represent maintenance of an alanine/pyruvate exchange hub rather than independent origin. It is included cautiously as a downstream biochemical redistribution process (Matsubara et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Chiral enrichment and selection of L-alanine from alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"crystallization, mineral adsorption, peptide-assisted selection, wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Racemic alanine undergoes enantioenrichment through selective adsorption, crystallization, or diastereomeric amplification, yielding an L-enriched product pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Prebiotic chemistry does not justify direct exclusive formation of L-alanine; a more defensible approach is postsynthetic chiral enrichment from racemic alanine via mineral templating or solution-phase amplification mechanisms. This addresses the stereochemical gap noted in earlier attempts (Hazen et al., 2001; Klussmann et al., 2006).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct hydrothermal reductive amination route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is reduced and extended to pyruvate in vents, then pyruvate undergoes reductive amination to alanine followed by L-enrichment.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate decarboxylation Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate is thermally decarboxylated to acetaldehyde, which enters surface Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis to alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"FTT aldehyde route with formamide-derived cyanide\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry supplies acetaldehyde while surface dehydration of formate plus ammonia gives formamide and then HCN for Strecker synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"FTT aldehyde route with formaldehyde-derived cyanide pool\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde comes from hydrothermal CO hydrogenation, while formaldehyde generated hydrothermally is transferred to the surface and contributes to HCN formation before Strecker synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-fed cyanide and pyruvate-fed aldehyde convergence\",\n      \"description\": \"One branch makes pyruvate then acetaldehyde, while a second branch turns hydrothermal formate into formamide and HCN; both converge at Strecker alanine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual hydrothermal input route to aminonitrile\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal chemistry independently supplies acetaldehyde and formaldehyde; after transfer to the surface, formaldehyde helps populate the cyanide pool and acetaldehyde undergoes Strecker synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Minimal vent-to-surface aminonitrile path\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate is decarboxylated to acetaldehyde; cyanide arises from formamide at the surface; Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis furnish alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal direct synthesis with biochemical chiral selection\",\n      \"description\": \"Alanine arises directly from pyruvate reductive amination in vents and is subsequently enriched to the L-form during later prebiotic selection.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldehyde-first route independent of pyruvate\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde is formed directly by hydrothermal FTT chemistry and joins with surface-generated HCN from formamide for the classic Strecker pathway to alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Network amplification via pyruvate-alanine exchange\",\n      \"description\": \"After initial alanine formation by either reductive amination or aminonitrile hydrolysis, pyruvate-centered transamination-like redistribution helps maintain the alanine pool before L-selection.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Alanine", "overall_strategy": "The network targets alanine through chemically stronger, literature-grounded routes centered on four hubs: pyruvate, acetaldehyde, hydrogen cyanide, and alanine aminonitrile. Hydrothermal chemistry fixes carbon from CO2 to formate, acetate, pyruvate, and acetaldehyde on iron-sulfur and oxide minerals. Surface chemistry supplies cyanide, aminonitrile formation, and hydrolysis under mineral-assisted wet-dry and UV regimes. Biochemical/prebiotic stages complete hydrolysis, transamination, and chiral enrichment/selection. Because abiotic syntheses generally yield racemic alanine, the network treats alanine formation as prebiotically plausible first, then routes to L-enrichment through mineral- and peptide-mediated selection rather than assuming primary enantioselective synthesis. Ten distinct connected pathways are defined to the target, with convergences at HCN, acetaldehyde, pyruvate, and alanine aminonitrile.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "acetic acid", "common_name": "acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "CHNO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H6N2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanenitrile", "common_name": "alanine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c1-3(4)2-5/h3H,4H2,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "L-alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)/t2-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Greigite-catalyzed reduction of CO2 to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Surface-mediated two-electron reduction of CO2 by H2 on iron-sulfur minerals yields adsorbed formate/formic acid.", "reasoning": "Reduction of CO2 to formate on FeS-family minerals is a core hydrothermal carbon-fixation step and is consistent with vent geochemistry and iron-sulfur world models (Martin et al., 2008; Barge et al., 2019; Roldan et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal homologation of formate to acetate", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "vent wall microcompartments, reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Formyl and carbonyl fragments generated on Fe-S surfaces couple and are further reduced to C2 carboxylate products.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis supports acetyl/thioester analog formation and acetate generation from CO2-, CO-, and H2-derived fragments (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Mineral-mediated synthesis of pyruvate from fixed C1/C2 carbon", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic hydrothermal flow, redox and pH gradients"}, "mechanism": "Sequential carbon fixation and carboxylation on mineral surfaces extend C1/C2 units to the alpha-keto acid pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is among the more plausible alpha-keto acid products in hydrothermal protometabolic networks, though exact mechanistic sequences remain partially unresolved; inclusion here connects experimentally supported C1/C2 fixation chemistry to protometabolic C3 products (Muchowska et al., 2019; Varma et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "thermal pulses in geothermal settings"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-keto acid decarboxylation releases CO2 and forms the corresponding aldehyde, acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde is chemically well established and provides a strong bridge from protometabolic keto-acids to Strecker-ready aldehydes under prebiotic heating regimes (Miller, 1957; Weber, 1981)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type formation of acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal, anoxic reducing fluid"}, "mechanism": "CO hydrogenation on metal/oxide surfaces generates mixed oxygenates including aldehydes such as acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrothermal synthesis on magnetite and reduced iron is a plausible source of simple aldehydes and alcohols, providing an independent route to acetaldehyde (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Reduction of CO2-derived carbon to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing hydrothermal fluids; mixed products expected"}, "mechanism": "Partial reduction of CO2 on reduced mineral surfaces yields low-molecular-weight oxygenates including formaldehyde in product mixtures.", "reasoning": "Formaldehyde production under hydrothermal reducing conditions is less selective than formate formation but remains plausible as part of mixed carbonyl inventories later concentrated at the surface; this step is included cautiously as a minor feeder route (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Cleaves, 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Photochemical generation of HCN from formamide", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, evaporitic or geothermal pool margins, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "UV-assisted dehydration/photolysis of formamide on mineral surfaces furnishes nitrile-bearing products including HCN.", "reasoning": "Formamide photochemistry is a widely discussed prebiotic source of cyanide-derived chemistry and nucleobase precursors under UV-irradiated mineral conditions (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface generation of HCN from formaldehyde and ammonia under UV-active conditions", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, drying-concentration cycles, anoxic atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical and redox-active surface chemistry converts reduced C1 carbonyl/nitrogen mixtures into nitrile products including HCN.", "reasoning": "Direct high-yield formaldehyde-to-HCN conversion is not a single canonical step, but UV-driven atmospheric and surface networks can generate HCN from reduced C/N feedstocks; here it is included as a connected feeder route to the cyanide pool rather than as an exclusive source (Patel et al., 2015; Rimmer & Rugheimer, 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface formamide formation from formate and ammonia during drying", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycles, dehydration in geothermal fields"}, "mechanism": "Drying-induced condensation of formate-derived formic acid equivalents with ammonia gives formamide.", "reasoning": "Formamide is plausibly concentrated and generated in drying surface environments from simple C1 precursors and ammonia, and serves as a key cyanide-related intermediate (Saladino et al., 2012; Pasek & Lauretta, 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Strecker synthesis of alanine aminonitrile from acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pools or tidal flats, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to produce 2-aminopropanenitrile.", "reasoning": "The Strecker route from acetaldehyde to alanine aminonitrile is among the strongest and most classic prebiotic pathways to alanine precursors (Miller, 1953; Miller, 